#: xml/ecpg.xml:221(title)
msgid "Choosing a Connection"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:222(para)
msgid "SQL statements in embedded SQL programs are by default executed on the current connection, that is, the most recently opened one. If an application needs to manage multiple connections, then there are two ways to handle this."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:229(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "EXEC SQL AT \n      <replaceable>connection-name</replaceable>SELECT\n      ...;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:227(para)
msgid "The first option is to explicitly choose a connection for each SQL statement, for example: <placeholder-1/>This option is particularly suitable if the application needs to use several connections in mixed order."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:234(para)
msgid "If your application uses multiple threads of execution, they cannot share a connection concurrently. You must either explicitly control access to the connection (using mutexes) or use a connection for each thread. If each thread uses its own connection, you will need to use the AT clause to specify which connection the thread will use."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:242(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "EXEC SQL SET CONNECTION \n      <replaceable>\n      connection-name</replaceable>;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:240(para)
msgid "The second option is to execute a statement to switch the current connection. That statement is: <placeholder-1/>This option is particularly convenient if many statements are to be executed on the same connection. It is not thread-aware."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:249(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "#include &lt;stdio.h&gt; EXEC SQL BEGIN\n      DECLARE SECTION; char dbname[1024]; EXEC SQL END DECLARE\n      SECTION; int main() { EXEC SQL CONNECT TO testdb1 AS con1\n      USER testuser; EXEC SQL CONNECT TO testdb2 AS con2 USER\n      testuser; EXEC SQL CONNECT TO testdb3 AS con3 USER testuser;\n      /* This query would be executed in the last opened database\n      \"testdb3\". */ EXEC SQL SELECT current_database() INTO\n      :dbname; printf(\"current=%s (should be testdb3)\\n\", dbname);\n      /* Using \"AT\" to run a query in \"testdb2\" */ EXEC SQL AT con2\n      SELECT current_database() INTO :dbname; printf(\"current=%s\n      (should be testdb2)\\n\", dbname); /* Switch the current\n      connection to \"testdb1\". */ EXEC SQL SET CONNECTION con1;\n      EXEC SQL SELECT current_database() INTO :dbname;\n      printf(\"current=%s (should be testdb1)\\n\", dbname); EXEC SQL\n      DISCONNECT ALL; return 0; }"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:247(para)
msgid "Here is an example program managing multiple database connections: <placeholder-1/>This example would produce this output: <screen>current=testdb3 (should be testdb3) current=testdb2\n      (should be testdb2) current=testdb1 (should be\n      testdb1)</screen>"
