#: xml/ecpg.xml:795(para)
msgid "To handle SQL character string data types, such as <type>varchar</type>and <type>text</type>, there are two possible ways to declare the host variables."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:803(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION; char\n        str[50]; EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:799(para)
msgid "One way is using <type>char[]</type>, an array of <type>char</type>, which is the most common way to handle character data in C. <placeholder-1/>Note that you have to take care of the length yourself. If you use this host variable as the target variable of a query which returns a string with more than 49 characters, a buffer overflow occurs."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:814(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "VARCHAR var[180];"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:816(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "struct varchar_var { int len; char\n        arr[180]; } var;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:809(para)
msgid "The other way is using the <type>VARCHAR</type>type, which is a special type provided by ECPG. The definition on an array of type <type>VARCHAR</type>is converted into a named <type>struct</type>for every variable. A declaration like: <placeholder-1/>is converted into: <placeholder-2/>The member <structfield>arr</structfield>hosts the string including a terminating zero byte. Thus, to store a string in a <type>VARCHAR</type>host variable, the host variable has to be declared with the length including the zero byte terminator. The member <structfield>len</structfield>holds the length of the string stored in the <structfield>arr</structfield>without the terminating zero byte. When a host variable is used as input for a query, if <literal>strlen(arr)</literal>and <structfield>len</structfield>are different, the shorter one is used."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:831(para)
msgid "<type>VARCHAR</type>can be written in upper or lower case, but not in mixed case."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:834(para)
msgid "<type>char</type>and <type>VARCHAR</type>host variables can also hold values of other SQL types, which will be stored in their string forms."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:841(title)
msgid "Accessing Special Data Types"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:842(para)
msgid "ECPG contains some special types that help you to interact easily with some special data types from the PostgreSQL server. In particular, it has implemented support for the <type>numeric</type>, <type>decimal</type>, <type>date</type>, <type>timestamp</type>, and <type>interval</type>types. These data types cannot usefully be mapped to primitive host variable types (such as <type>int</type>, <type>long long int</type>, or <type>char[]</type>), because they have a complex internal structure. Applications deal with these types by declaring host variables in special types and accessing them using functions in the pgtypes library. The pgtypes library, described in detail in <xref linkend=\"ecpg-pgtypes\">contains basic functions to deal with those types, such that you do not need to send a query to the SQL server just for adding an interval to a time stamp for example.</xref>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:864(para)
msgid "The follow subsections describe these special data types. For more details about pgtypes library functions, see <xref linkend=\"ecpg-pgtypes\">.</xref>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:869(title)
msgid "timestamp, date"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:871(para)
msgid "Here is a pattern for handling <type>timestamp</type>variables in the ECPG host application."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:877(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "#include\n          pgtypes_timestamp.h&gt;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:874(para)
msgid "First, the program has to include the header file for the <type>timestamp</type>type: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:881(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION; timestamp\n          ts; EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:879(para)
msgid "Next, declare a host variable as type <type>timestamp</type>in the declare section: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:889(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "EXEC SQL SELECT now()::timestamp INTO\n          :ts; printf(\"ts = %s\\n\",\n          PGTYPEStimestamp_to_asc(ts));"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:883(para)
msgid "And after reading a value into the host variable, process it using pgtypes library functions. In following example, the <type>timestamp</type>value is converted into text (ASCII) form with the <function>PGTYPEStimestamp_to_asc()</function>function: <placeholder-1/>This example will show some result like following: <screen>ts = 2010-06-27 18:03:56.949343</screen>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:894(para)
msgid "In addition, the DATE type can be handled in the same way. The program has to include <filename>pgtypes_date.h</filename>, declare a host variable as the date type and convert a DATE value into a text form using <function>PGTYPESdate_to_asc()</function>function. For more details about the pgtypes library functions, see <xref linkend=\"ecpg-pgtypes\">.</xref>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:905(para)
msgid "The handling of the <type>interval</type>type is also similar to the <type>timestamp</type>and <type>date</type>types. It is required, however, to allocate memory for an <type>interval</type>type value explicitly. In other words, the memory space for the variable has to be allocated in the heap memory, not in the stack memory."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:915(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "#include stdio.h&gt; #include\n          stdlib.h&gt; #include pgtypes_interval.h&gt; int\n          main(void) { EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION; interval\n          *in; EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION; EXEC SQL CONNECT TO\n          testdb; in = PGTYPESinterval_new(); EXEC SQL SELECT '1\n          min'::interval INTO :in; printf(\"interval = %s\\n\",\n          PGTYPESinterval_to_asc(in)); PGTYPESinterval_free(in);\n          EXEC SQL COMMIT; EXEC SQL DISCONNECT ALL; return 0;\n          }"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:914(para)
msgid "Here is an example program: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:926(title)
msgid "numeric, decimal"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:927(para)
msgid "The handling of the <type>numeric</type>and <type>decimal</type>types is similar to the <type>interval</type>type: It requires defining a pointer, allocating some memory space on the heap, and accessing the variable using the pgtypes library functions. For more details about the pgtypes library functions, see <xref linkend=\"ecpg-pgtypes\">.</xref>"
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:936(para)
msgid "No functions are provided specifically for the <type>decimal</type>type. An application has to convert it to a <type>numeric</type>variable using a pgtypes library function to do further processing."
msgstr ""

#: xml/ecpg.xml:944(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "#include stdio.h&gt; #include\n          stdlib.h&gt; #include pgtypes_numeric.h&gt; EXEC SQL\n          WHENEVER SQLERROR STOP; int main(void) { EXEC SQL BEGIN\n          DECLARE SECTION; numeric *num; numeric *num2; decimal\n          *dec; EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION; EXEC SQL CONNECT TO\n          testdb; num = PGTYPESnumeric_new(); dec =\n          PGTYPESdecimal_new(); EXEC SQL SELECT\n          12.345::numeric(4,2), 23.456::decimal(4,2) INTO :num,\n          :dec; printf(\"numeric = %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num,\n          0)); printf(\"numeric = %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num,\n          1)); printf(\"numeric = %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num,\n          2)); /* Convert decimal to numeric to show a decimal\n          value. */ num2 = PGTYPESnumeric_new();\n          PGTYPESnumeric_from_decimal(dec, num2); printf(\"decimal =\n          %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num2, 0)); printf(\"decimal =\n          %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num2, 1)); printf(\"decimal =\n          %s\\n\", PGTYPESnumeric_to_asc(num2, 2));\n          PGTYPESnumeric_free(num2); PGTYPESdecimal_free(dec);\n          PGTYPESnumeric_free(num); EXEC SQL COMMIT; EXEC SQL\n          DISCONNECT ALL; return 0; }"
msgstr ""

